const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is a lien waiver in construction?',
    answer:
      'A lien waiver is a document in which the signing party — a subcontractor, supplier, or lower-tier sub — gives up the right to file a mechanics lien against the property in exchange for payment. The waiver type (conditional or unconditional, progress or final) determines exactly what rights you are releasing and when that release takes effect.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between conditional and unconditional lien waivers?',
    answer:
      'A conditional waiver takes effect only when payment actually clears — if the check bounces or the wire never arrives, the waiver is void and your lien rights remain intact. An unconditional waiver is effective the moment you sign it, regardless of whether payment is received. Never sign an unconditional waiver before payment has cleared your account.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What are the four types of construction lien waivers?',
    answer:
      'The four standard types are: (1) Conditional waiver on progress payment — covers a billing period; takes effect on receipt of that payment. (2) Unconditional waiver on progress payment — covers a billing period; effective immediately on signing. (3) Conditional waiver on final payment — covers all work through final payment; takes effect on receipt. (4) Unconditional waiver on final payment — waives all remaining lien rights; effective immediately on signing.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I be required to sign a lien waiver before I am paid?',
    answer:
      "GCs commonly require a conditional waiver at the time of payment — that's standard practice and protects both parties because the waiver only activates when payment clears. Some GCs attempt to require unconditional waivers before payment is issued. Whether that's enforceable depends on state law; several states prohibit requiring unconditional waivers as a condition of payment. Know your state's rules before you agree to it.",
  },
  {
    question: "What happens if I sign an unconditional waiver and payment doesn't come through?",
    answer:
      "If you signed a conditional waiver, your lien rights are still intact — the waiver never activated because the payment condition was not met. If you signed an unconditional waiver and payment didn't arrive, you have likely waived your lien rights and your remaining recourse is a breach of contract claim, which is harder to pursue with no property lien behind it. That distinction is not a formality.",
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Construction Lien Waivers Explained | BuildWorkPro"
  description="What are conditional and unconditional lien waivers? A subcontractor's guide to all four types, when to sign each, and what to watch in the language."
>
  <Header />
  <main class="pt-32 pb-20">
    <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="mb-12">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-brand-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Blog</p>
        <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight">
          Construction Lien Waivers Explained: Conditional vs. Unconditional
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-400">Published June 19, 2026 · 8 min read</p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <p>
          Every subcontractor encounters lien waivers — usually with a check attached and a request
          to sign before payment goes through. Most people sign without reading closely, which is
          fine right up until something goes wrong. A lien waiver is a legal document. The type you
          sign, and when you sign it, determines whether you retain any protection if payment
          doesn't materialize.
        </p>
        <p>
          This guide covers what lien waivers are, the four types used in construction, and the one
          rule that protects you on every job: never sign an unconditional waiver before payment has
          cleared.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-100 p-6 not-prose my-8">
          <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">Key takeaways</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-600 list-disc pl-5">
            <li>
              A lien waiver trades lien rights for payment — the type you sign determines what you
              give up and when.
            </li>
            <li>
              Conditional waivers take effect only when payment clears; unconditional waivers are
              effective immediately on signing.
            </li>
            <li>
              Progress waivers cover a billing period; final waivers release all remaining claims
              through the final payment.
            </li>
            <li>Never sign an unconditional waiver before the payment has cleared your account.</li>
            <li>
              Many states prescribe mandatory waiver forms — using the correct state form matters
              for enforceability.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>What is a lien waiver?</h2>
        <p>
          A mechanics lien is a legal claim a contractor, subcontractor, or supplier can record
          against a property when they are not paid for work or materials. A lien encumbers the
          property's title and can block a sale or refinance until the claim is resolved. It is one
          of the most effective collection tools available to subs and suppliers.
        </p>
        <p>
          A lien waiver is the document that gives up that right — in full or in part — in exchange
          for payment (or the promise of it). Owners and GCs collect lien waivers throughout a
          project to confirm that everyone in the payment chain has been paid and the property can
          close out free of lien claims. They are typically required at each billing period and
          again at final payment.
        </p>

        <h2>The four types of construction lien waivers</h2>
        <p>
          Two variables define every lien waiver: <strong>conditional vs. unconditional</strong> (when
          the waiver activates) and <strong>progress vs. final</strong> (what period it covers). Combined,
          those produce four types:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Conditional waiver on progress payment.</strong> Covers a specific billing period.
            Takes effect only when the payment for that period clears. This is the standard form exchanged
            alongside a progress payment — you provide the waiver, the GC issues the check, and the waiver
            activates only when payment is received.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Unconditional waiver on progress payment.</strong> Covers a billing period but takes
            effect immediately on signing, regardless of payment. Appropriate only after a progress payment
            has already cleared your account.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Conditional waiver on final payment.</strong> Waives all lien rights through the final
            payment amount, but only takes effect when final payment clears. The standard form to provide
            when requesting a final payment or retainage release.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Unconditional waiver on final payment.</strong> Waives all lien rights through final
            payment, effective immediately on signing. Only sign this after final payment has cleared
            your account — it leaves no recourse if payment is reversed or fails to arrive.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Conditional vs. unconditional: why the difference matters</h2>
        <p>
          A <strong>conditional waiver</strong> is contingent on payment. If the check bounces, the wire
          never arrives, or the GC stops responding, the waiver never activated and your lien rights remain
          intact. The waiver was a promise contingent on receipt of funds, not a completed transaction.
        </p>
        <p>
          An <strong>unconditional waiver</strong> has no payment condition. You signed it, it is effective,
          and your lien rights for that scope are gone — even if you were never paid. If payment does
          not follow an unconditional waiver, your remaining recourse is a breach of contract claim, which
          is harder to pursue and has no property lien to back it up.
        </p>
        <p>
          GCs commonly request conditional waivers at the time of payment and unconditional waivers
          after confirming payment has been received. That is a reasonable and standard workflow.
          The problem arises when a GC tries to require an unconditional waiver before the payment
          goes out — some do, and some states prohibit it. Know the rule in your state before you
          agree to it.
        </p>

        <h2>Progress waivers vs. final waivers</h2>
        <p>
          The progress vs. final distinction is about scope. A <strong>progress waiver</strong> covers
          a defined billing period — typically tied to a pay application payment. It says: "I waive lien
          rights for work completed and billed through this payment." The next billing period starts fresh;
          you are not releasing anything beyond the period stated on the waiver.
        </p>
        <p>
          A <strong>final waiver</strong> covers everything — all work performed through the final payment
          date. When you sign a conditional waiver on final payment alongside your last billing, you are
          saying that once final payment clears, all lien rights on the project are resolved. That includes
          any balance remaining, retainage release, and any pending amounts.
        </p>
        <p>
          Lien waiver requirements connect directly to the billing workflow. On AIA-style pay
          applications, each progress payment cycle typically involves a conditional progress
          waiver; the final billing — often the same submission that requests retainage release —
          involves a conditional final waiver. Our
          <a href="/blog/aia-pay-application-guide/">AIA pay application guide</a> covers how the billing
          documents and payment cycle fit together.
        </p>

        <h2>When to sign each type</h2>
        <p>The right waiver for each situation:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>With a progress payment request:</strong> Conditional waiver on progress payment.
            Exchange it with the payment or provide it as the payment is issued. The waiver activates
            only when payment clears.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>After a progress payment has cleared:</strong> Unconditional waiver on progress payment.
            Safe to provide once you have confirmed the funds are in your account.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>With a final payment and retainage release request:</strong> Conditional waiver on
            final payment. Gives the GC and owner the assurance they need for closeout while keeping your
            protection until the money arrives.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>After final payment and retainage have cleared:</strong> Unconditional waiver on final
            payment. Your lien rights are effectively zero at this point anyway; this closes out the GC's
            file cleanly.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What to watch out for in waiver language</h2>
        <p>
          Not all waivers are written the same way. Beyond the conditional vs. unconditional
          distinction, watch for:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Broad release language.</strong> Some waivers attempt to release claims beyond lien
            rights — including claims for change orders, disputed amounts, or delay damages. If the waiver
            purports to release anything beyond lien rights for the stated payment, push back or consult
            an attorney before signing.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Dollar amount and through-date.</strong> Every waiver should specify the payment amount
            it covers and the date through which work is covered. Waivers with blank or open-ended amounts
            are a problem.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>State-prescribed forms.</strong> Several states — California, Texas, and Arizona among
            them — have mandatory statutory lien waiver forms. Using non-standard language in those states
            can affect enforceability. If you are working in a state with mandatory forms, use them.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Who has to sign.</strong> GCs often need lien waivers from your lower-tier subs and
            material suppliers, not just from you. Know whether you are responsible for collecting those
            before final payment will be released.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Lien waivers and retainage release</h2>
        <p>
          Lien waivers and retainage are linked at closeout. Most contracts require the sub to
          provide a conditional waiver on final payment before retainage is released — and that
          release is the last payment on the project. Getting the exchange right matters.
        </p>
        <p>
          The sequence at closeout typically looks like this: you submit a final pay application and
          provide a conditional final waiver. Once the GC receives it, they process the payment —
          including the withheld retainage. After you confirm payment has cleared, you provide the
          unconditional final waiver. The file is closed.
        </p>
        <p>
          If the retainage release is delayed — because the GC has not yet received funds from the
          owner, or because the punch list is not resolved — your conditional waiver protects you
          throughout the wait. That is exactly what the conditional form is designed for.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a deeper look at how retainage accumulates, when it releases, and what to negotiate
          before signing the subcontract, see our <a href="/blog/retainage-construction-guide/"
            >retainage guide</a
          >. Your <a href="/features/change-orders/">change orders</a> also feed into this: every approved
          change increases the contract sum, which means the final payment amount — and the correct dollar
          amount on the final waiver — should reflect all approved changes.
        </p>

        <h2>Lien waivers and your pay applications in BuildWorkPro</h2>
        <p>
          BuildWorkPro does not generate lien waivers — those are legal documents typically produced
          from state-specific forms. What it does handle is the billing side of the equation: each
          <a href="/features/pay-applications/">pay application</a> has a payment summary showing the
          amount due for the period and the retainage withheld, so you always know the exact dollar figure
          to reference when completing a conditional waiver.
        </p>
        <p>
          Keeping your pay applications current and accurate is what makes the waiver amounts
          defensible. The payment summary rolls up the schedule of values, this period's billing,
          and retainage into a single amount due — that number goes on the conditional waiver.
        </p>
      </div>

