      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <h2>Practical rules for handling lien waivers</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Default to conditional until payment clears.</strong> Conditional waivers are standard;
            there is no legitimate reason to require an unconditional waiver before payment is issued.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Read the dollar amount and through-date before you sign.</strong> Both should match
            the payment you are receiving. Blank amounts and open-ended dates are red flags.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Watch for extra release language.</strong> A waiver that releases "all claims" rather
            than specifically "mechanics lien rights" may do far more than you intend.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Know your state's forms.</strong> If your state has mandatory statutory waiver forms,
            use them — non-standard language may not hold up.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Keep a copy of every waiver you sign.</strong> They are part of the payment record
            for each project.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

